WEBVTT

00:01.820 --> 00:08.110
Here's another thing I figured out.

00:08.190 --> 00:16.362
Let's say you're in Mexico and it's 1950.

00:16.382 --> 00:18.445
And you have an aunt that dies.

00:19.106 --> 00:20.588
She leaves you 100 pesos.

00:22.872 --> 00:27.499
So you say a peso at that time was like 50 cents on the dollar.

00:27.659 --> 00:30.223
One American dollar would buy two pesos.

00:32.110 --> 00:34.834
because there's still gold and silver behind the peso.

00:34.854 --> 00:36.936
So you say, well, I don't need the hundred dollars.

00:36.956 --> 00:41.362
I'm going to put it away for savings.

00:41.382 --> 00:44.446
You know, hide it in the cookie jar, so to speak.

00:44.466 --> 00:50.854
So you go to the bank and you buy a 50 peso gold coin and you put away a 50 peso bill.

00:54.078 --> 00:55.500
Here it is, 1990.

00:55.520 --> 01:00.126
You say, well, I'm going to go, I remember that

01:00.713 --> 01:08.000
little savings I put away, I'm going to go and get it and see what I can get for it.

01:08.020 --> 01:19.651
That 50 peso gold coin's worth about 450 American dollars, and that 50 peso bill, American dollar, it's about 2,900 to one now.

01:20.292 --> 01:22.774
So you divide 50 into 2,900.

01:22.814 --> 01:27.919
You know, it takes 2,900 paper pesos to make a dollar where

01:28.422 --> 01:31.846
50 gold pesos equal 450 American dollars.

01:31.866 --> 01:33.988
That's how the government swindled people, currency.

01:34.008 --> 01:36.451
So that's why I was putting my money into that.

01:38.053 --> 01:53.670
Unless a hot bargain come along, like, you know, if I could buy a big collection of books or stained glass windows or something that I could work, that I needed for research or

01:54.393 --> 02:07.091
That Oregon collection that they described, was that one of your favorite collections?

02:07.111 --> 02:07.491
Oregon collections?

02:07.511 --> 02:11.918
The one that they came from Oregon that they described yesterday?

02:11.938 --> 02:13.380
The stuff that came from Oregon?

02:13.400 --> 02:14.061
Oh, not really.

02:14.081 --> 02:14.441
I don't know that.

02:14.461 --> 02:18.908
It seemed like the most intense, the most extensive single collection.

02:20.430 --> 02:21.711
Oh, what, the manuscripts?

02:21.732 --> 02:21.832
Yeah.

02:21.852 --> 02:22.813
No, I'm not familiar with manuscripts that much.

02:24.751 --> 02:29.717
They said $500,000, $600,000.

02:29.737 --> 02:39.290
No, that was the... I think that was that Norberg Chronicle stuff.

02:39.310 --> 02:40.732
No, no, I thought it was the guy from Oregon.

02:40.892 --> 02:43.435
Oh, yeah, yeah.

02:43.455 --> 02:48.301
I never got a chance to research that stuff, to read it, to use it.

02:48.321 --> 02:49.663
I'm glad they got it back.

02:50.264 --> 02:52.146
That's salvation.

02:52.166 --> 02:53.408
I wish I could have read it.

02:55.058 --> 03:03.045
Now, is that something that you had actually wanted, or was it one of the opportunities that presented itself?

03:03.065 --> 03:05.927
Well, in a way, yeah.

03:05.947 --> 03:06.948
In a way, the latter?

03:06.968 --> 03:11.733
Yeah.

03:11.753 --> 03:22.061
Well, it may have been such a long time before they realized it wasn't there.

03:22.082 --> 03:22.182
Yeah.

03:22.202 --> 03:24.964
That one's just almost as wild as a piece of string.

03:25.653 --> 03:27.956
You're going to tell me about that.

03:27.976 --> 03:28.977
Oh, after the trial.

03:31.820 --> 03:33.262
Even if I shut this off?

03:33.322 --> 03:34.443
No, after the trial.

03:36.185 --> 03:38.428
OK.

03:38.908 --> 03:42.953
OK, good.

03:42.973 --> 03:47.238
Well, a person has to be resourceful, you know.

03:47.258 --> 03:50.181
I think this is a pleasant experience for all of us.

03:50.221 --> 03:51.082
Oh, yeah, Adam.

03:52.364 --> 03:53.805
Good to have you guys along.

03:53.825 --> 03:55.187
And with friends.

03:55.420 --> 03:56.341
Isn't it nice?

03:56.841 --> 03:57.001
Yes.

03:59.323 --> 04:00.945
Now, were you ever a Boy Scout or anything?

04:01.305 --> 04:02.046
I was a Cub Scout.

04:02.106 --> 04:03.847
Were you?

04:03.867 --> 04:08.652
Did you acquire a lot of this resourcefulness, do you think, from, uh... No, I acquired it.

04:09.012 --> 04:09.953
Scouting or...?

04:09.973 --> 04:13.496
I acquired it on the street, and the necessity's a mother of invention.

04:13.536 --> 04:20.862
I just sort of figured things out, you know.

04:20.882 --> 04:23.685
So you could really write a book, you know, about this.

04:23.705 --> 04:24.645
Oh, you think so.

04:24.665 --> 04:25.326
About this.

04:25.728 --> 04:26.649
Oh, yeah.

04:26.749 --> 04:29.332
Or we could really talk about it at length.

04:29.452 --> 04:36.420
I mean, I think people would be fascinated to learn how this was done.

04:36.980 --> 04:37.180
Oh.

04:37.481 --> 04:45.249
Not how for the sake of providing a blueprint, but I think the experiences, the anecdotal... Oh, yeah.

04:45.269 --> 04:47.191
Yeah, it was interesting.

04:47.211 --> 04:48.893
It was a high, you know.

04:48.933 --> 04:50.014
Was it a high?

04:51.015 --> 04:51.175
Yeah.

04:51.195 --> 04:53.558
Like digging in that box at an auction and...

04:55.276 --> 04:59.982
finding the last late-side classic you need to complete your set.

05:01.444 --> 05:13.501
In your mind's eye, was the scope of what you had established for yourself, for your collection?

05:13.521 --> 05:18.027
I didn't really understand the scope of it.

05:18.631 --> 05:20.533
I'm not talking about the massiveness.

05:20.593 --> 05:21.794
No, I mean the quality.

05:21.894 --> 05:27.760
The quality, but there was certainly, you understood the focus, because you established the focus, the focus of the collection.

05:28.001 --> 05:28.581
What do you mean?

05:28.661 --> 05:32.185
You're collecting areas, the particular areas.

05:32.205 --> 05:33.666
Well, I'd read of those areas.

05:33.746 --> 05:36.429
That's how I learned about them and was curious about them.

05:37.310 --> 05:44.117
But I'm saying, did you ever feel that you were close to completing the film for the collection?

05:44.137 --> 05:45.178
Yeah, I was getting there.

05:45.968 --> 05:50.836
I was right.

05:50.976 --> 05:57.787
I had a feeling I was getting close to the magnitude of Streeter in the Americana.

05:58.849 --> 06:01.994
I'd just love to see the bibliography and compare it.

06:02.154 --> 06:04.297
I've got a copy of Streeter.

06:04.397 --> 06:04.938
I have Streeter.

06:05.058 --> 06:06.200
I got it from Jenkins.

06:07.362 --> 06:09.065
I got mine from Gladly Martin.

06:09.165 --> 06:10.367
I got that at the Martin sale.

06:11.008 --> 06:12.330
And I'd like to compare

06:13.087 --> 06:19.414
If the government would do an accurate survey, I'd like to compare my... Of course, they're not going to break it down by subject.

06:19.494 --> 06:21.596
I think they're going to break it down by provenance.

06:21.656 --> 06:25.821
I don't think the government's capable of doing that kind of a bibliographic comparison.

06:26.181 --> 06:26.902
No, no, no.

06:26.922 --> 06:28.684
They're not capable of doing much of anything.

06:28.724 --> 06:38.354
I mean, you're asking now for a pretty sophisticated... I mean, let's be real here.

06:38.374 --> 06:41.758
They can't even use the word presently correctly.

06:41.778 --> 06:41.878
Yeah.

06:42.179 --> 06:45.184
But I could do that, go through there.

06:45.204 --> 06:53.077
In fact, in my own head, if you gave me a copy of Streeter, I could sit down and annotate that.

06:53.678 --> 06:55.041
I knew in my mind what I had.

06:55.061 --> 06:57.084
Was Streeter something of a model for you?

07:00.430 --> 07:01.812
Well, in imprints.

07:01.832 --> 07:03.435
He was real strong in imprints.

07:03.455 --> 07:08.203
Did you emulate a model for you to emulate the collector?

07:09.145 --> 07:10.607
Well, it depends.

07:10.647 --> 07:12.949
Streeter, like I say, I like it for imprints.

07:12.969 --> 07:15.912
He had, like, newspaper for his publishing and that.

07:15.932 --> 07:20.337
I'd say Brindley was more of a problem.

07:20.377 --> 07:21.618
Do you have a Brindley catalog?

07:21.678 --> 07:22.559
I have three sets.

07:22.959 --> 07:24.461
Oh, really?

07:24.621 --> 07:24.821
Yep.

