08:40.547 --> 08:43.611
And we're back in, uh... Oskaloosa, Iowa.

08:45.975 --> 08:48.378
This is where we had lunch or whatever.

08:48.398 --> 08:50.321
I've had a flight lunch.

08:50.341 --> 08:51.362
The chili was great.

08:52.404 --> 08:55.088
And the, uh, let me see if I can remember the name of that block.

08:55.368 --> 08:56.309
What, Kinkleman?

08:56.430 --> 08:58.292
The, uh... Frankel block.

08:58.372 --> 08:58.853
Frankel.

08:59.575 --> 09:06.661
You know, one of my favorite ethnic folk bands was a Jewish New York folk band.

09:06.681 --> 09:10.765
It was Lieutenant Josh Frankel's Yiddish Dance Band.

09:10.985 --> 09:20.754
And he was popular in New York around World War I, and I just loved his records, you know.

09:20.774 --> 09:27.300
The more contemporary band was a band called, I think, Marty Katz and his Katzenjammers.

09:27.380 --> 09:28.941
He was back in the 40s.

09:29.528 --> 09:33.835
But, you know, I like ethnic music.

09:34.696 --> 09:43.591
German military marches for Germany and Russian bala-laka orchestras for Russia and Jewish.

09:43.611 --> 09:47.537
Well, I'm Greek, you know, I do all of that.

09:47.872 --> 09:49.835
The Greek bouzoukia music.

09:49.855 --> 09:51.397
Oh, yeah.

09:51.557 --> 09:52.939
You probably haven't met many Greeks.

09:52.959 --> 09:54.221
There aren't many.

09:54.241 --> 09:55.202
There are some in Iowa.

09:55.222 --> 09:58.046
I meet them usually in restaurants.

09:58.086 --> 09:59.207
We own them.

09:59.227 --> 10:02.512
The Greeks own all the restaurants.

10:04.755 --> 10:11.684
That's right.

10:11.704 --> 10:11.985
You know them?

10:12.005 --> 10:14.668
I don't, I don't know.

10:14.688 --> 10:15.109
Johnny's best friend.

10:15.129 --> 10:15.870
There used to be a teak pole for him.

